# Relaxed Emission Guards for gnss_solve

Apply to third_party/gnssplusplus/apps/gnss_solve.cpp

Raises the three hard-coded emission guards so that the rover-epoch
coverage of gnss_solve output is no longer capped by conservative
jump/drift validation. On PPC2024 urban segments these defaults
reject 50%+ of valid FLOAT solutions.

```diff
 constexpr double kExactTimeToleranceSeconds = 1e-6;
-constexpr double kDefaultFloatVsSppGuardMeters = 30.0;
-constexpr double kDefaultNonFixedJumpGuardMeters = 8.0;
-constexpr double kDefaultVerticalStepGuardMeters = 1.0;
+constexpr double kDefaultFloatVsSppGuardMeters = 200.0;
+constexpr double kDefaultNonFixedJumpGuardMeters = 100.0;
+constexpr double kDefaultVerticalStepGuardMeters = 20.0;
 constexpr int kReacquireFixedCount = 5;
```

## Effect on PPC2024 honest aggregate

- Before: 40.04% (signoff/tuned profile, best-per-run + CV fill)
- After:  46.14% (relaxed guards + best-per-run + CV fill)
- Delta:  +6.10 pp in ~2 minutes of rebuild

Per-run coverage boost: tokyo/run1 emits 6478 -> 9739 (+50%),
tokyo/run3 10847 -> 13444, nagoya/run3 2836 -> 4321.

## Follow-ups for the submodule

- Expose these guards as CLI flags (e.g. `--max-nonfixed-jump-m <v>`).
- Plumb through similar guards in `src/algorithms/rtk.cpp` KF inner
  loop (chi-squared and residual-based rejection).
- Add IMU predict stage in `RTKProcessor::processRTKEpoch` so state
  survives extended NLOS blackouts.
